  "Idea": "This paper introduces 'Recursive Unary Decomposition' (RUD) as a foundational principle for discovering hierarchical structure in arbitrary functions. The central hypothesis is that any multivariate function f(x₁, x₂, ..., xₙ) can be expressed—or closely approximated—as g(u(xᵢ), h(x₁, ..., xᵢ₋₁, xᵢ₊₁, ..., xₙ)), where u is a unary function acting solely on one input xᵢ, and h processes the remaining inputs, with g combining their outputs. This decomposition isolates a single variable’s influence through u while preserving global functionality via composition. Crucially, this process is recursive: h itself can undergo RUD until base cases (e.g., constants, identity functions, or irreducible bivariate kernels) are reached, yielding a tree-structured representation of the original function. We develop an algorithmic framework to induce such decompositions from data by evaluating candidate splits using criteria such as variance reduction, mutual information gain, and symbolic fit quality. At each step, the algorithm selects the variable xᵢ and form of u that maximizes modularity and minimizes residual error. To ensure interpretability, all discovered components are constrained to lie within a library of elementary functions (polynomials, exponentials, conditionals, etc.), enabling symbolic reconstruction. Applications include extracting scientific laws from experimental data, simplifying neural network decision boundaries, and enhancing post-hoc explanations in AI systems. For instance, in physics, Kepler’s third law T² ∝ R³ could be decomposed into u(R)=R³, h(T)=T², combined multiplicatively—a structure our method would recover without prior domain knowledge. In machine learning, RUD can distill deep networks into readable rule trees by recursively decomposing activation pathways. Validations will involve synthetic benchmarks with known ground-truth hierarchies, real-world scientific datasets (e.g., fluid dynamics equations), and integration with LLMs for se